We studied 108 people (72 women and 36 men, aged 46-67 years, average age 57.0 ± 8.5 years) with MetS, which was diagnosed according to International Diabetes Federation (IDF) criteria 200510, with the following criteria:


abdominal obesity;



triglycerides (TG) ≥150 mg/dL or on TG-lowering treatment;



high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C) <40 mg/dL in men or <50 mg/dL in women, or treatment for low HDL-C;



blood pressure ≥130/≥85 mm Hg or on antihypertensive medication;



glucose: ≥100 mg/dL or on treatment of DM.

All the study participants were volunteers and signed an informed consent form before their inclusion in the study, and the study was approved by the local Ethics Committee of the Medical University in Lodz. The Helsinki declaration recommendations were observed.

Vascular changes in the fundus of the eye (angiopathy and/or retinopathy) were assessed in ophthalmoscopy and flourescence angiography. The level of retinopathy development was assessed according to World Health Organization (WHO) classification for diabetic retinopathy12:


nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy without maculopathy;



nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy with maculopathy;



preproliferative diabetic retinopathy;



proliferative diabetic retinopathy without complications;



proliferative diabetic retinopathy with complications.

For statistical analysis, the results of examination of the fundus of the eye were coded with a scale of 0 to 6, where 0 = lack of vascular changes, 1 = angiopathy, and 2 to 6 = next levels of retinopathy.
